BIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "uterine ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9692055583000183, "span": {"begin": 1931, "end": 1941}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mRNA", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.7243347764015198, "span": {"begin": 1950, "end": 1954}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "nuclear ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9199255704879761, "span": {"begin": 2006, "end": 2016}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997822642326355, "span": {"begin": 2043, "end": 2051}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2091, "end": 2093}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2152, "end": 2154}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2330, "end": 2332}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2397, "end": 2399}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2434, "end": 2436}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER mRNA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9620745182037354, "span": {"begin": 2454, "end": 2461}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2466, "end": 2468}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2480, "end": 2482}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2542, "end": 2544}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER mRNA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9894418716430664, "span": {"begin": 2675, "end": 2682}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2684, "end": 2686}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "polyadenylated RNA", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.905845046043396, "span": {"begin": 2692, "end": 2710}}], "text": "The biological plausibility of this KERs is linked to the physiological role of E2 on estrogen-responsive tissues of all mammals.  The uterus in rodents and the human undergoes cyclical changes of growth and degeneration (Fig. 10 and 11). In both species, estrogens produced from the developing follicles stimulate endometrial growth, and progesterone is responsible for converting the estrogen primed endometrium into a receptive state. In rodents, if pregnancy does not occur, dioestrus (secretory phase in humans, cycle days 15&ndash;28) terminates with regression of the corpus luteum, and the endometrium is resorbed (menstruation in humans, cycle days 1&ndash;5). During proestrus (proliferative phase in humans, cycle days 6&ndash;14) follicles develop and start to produce estrogens that stimulate endometrial growth. During oestrous (peri-ovulatory period in humans, cycle days 13&ndash;15) ovarian follicles mature. The magnitude of uterine growth stimulation is largely dependent upon the duration of bioavailable E2 and receptor interaction (Groothius et al., 2007).      Bergman et al., 1992 studied the role of oestradiol during the mouse oestrus cycle. The study demonstrated that on proestrus, when plasma E2 levels are at the highest, the cell nuclear ER concentration in uterus was greater than metestrus. This increase was attributable to an increase in total cellular ER (cytosolic and nuclear) and secondarily to activation of ER (measured by its distribution from cytosolic to the nuclear fraction) (Tables 4 and 5).  Table 4. Uterine weight, DNA, RNA, and plasma concentrations of E2 during the estrous cycle of C57BL/6J mice. from Bergman et al., 1992    Table 5. Uterine weight, DNA, RNA, and plasma concentrations of E2 in E2-treated OVX mice. from Bergman et al., 1992    Overall, this study demonstrated in mice a strong association between E2 and the biosynthesis and intracellular distribution of the uterine ER and its mRNA.  The study indicated that the basis for increased nuclear ER on proestrus involves two estrogen-dependent components: 1. activation of ER to a nucleophilic state and 2. increased concentration of ER available for activation, the latter accounting for most of the increase in nuclear ER. The process probably begins early on the day of proestrus with increased activation of ER in response to the rising levels of E2. Increased activation of ER leads to increased DNA binding of ER, which increases ER mRNA and ER. Increased ER provides the substrate for a further increase in DNA-bound ER, which serves to amplify the effect of the rising E2 in a feed-forward cascade that ultimately leads to the dramatic increases in ER mRNA, ER, and polyadenylated RNA that are observed at midday on proestrus (Bergman et al., 2005).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:09:09 +0000 2026"}